flowRoot.flowPara: Contemporary neuroimaging studies are typically unique in their structure and result in the generation of heterogenous datasets, varying in complexity from simple text files to hierarchical, multi-dimensional image formats. To further complicate data harmonization and sharing efforts, a study is typically composed of multiple imaging protocols and often multiple groups of subjects. Lack of consensus on formats and data organisation leads to misunderstanding and time wasted on rearranging data or rewriting scripts to accommodate particular file formats and directory structures, as well as a possible cause for errors.

Simplified example of a BIDS dataset. File and folder names follow a strict set of rules enabling finding or identifying relevant files without the need to consult addition dictionaries. Each filename includes a set of key/value pairs describing subject ID, task name, acquisition parameter set label, run number etc. Each filename ends with a suffix uniquely identifying its type.

Key/value data. Key/value dictionaries are used to store acquisition parameters not included in the NIFTI headers, data dictionaries, dataset metadata, and sampling information for physiological data. JSON was used to store dictionary data due to its simplicity, support for linked data and validation schemas. Each JSON file follows a specification of well defined optional and mandatory fields. In addition data producers can extend any dictionary with their own custom fields.

Representation of tabular data. Tabular way of storing data is used in the BIDS standard to represent participant demographic phenotypic data (example above), session and scan related timing and behavioral data as well as task fMRI timing information. Tab Separated Value (TSV) files were chosen to represent tabular data due to their simplicity and ease of representing strings that include commas.

Representation of binary imaging data. Multiple file formats have been used to represent neuroimaging data in the past (DICOM, AFNI, MINC, ANALYZE etc.), however only NIfTI has been widely adopted. Despite its shortcomings (memory mapped random access of compressed data, limited capacity of the header to store metadata) it is the most supported file format across neuroimaging data analysis software (FSL, SPM, AFNI, MRTrix, FreeSurfer etc.). Shortcomings of NIfTI in terms of metadata representation have been dealt with using JSON dictionaries.

The BIDS Validator. To make it easy for data producers to validate consistency and completeness of a dataset we have developed an easy to use validator. The tool was written in JavaScript and is available as a web app (working client side with no need to upload any data) or a command line tool. The validator checks adherence to the BIDS standard as well as consistency of scanning parameters across subjects.

Other tools using BIDS. The software ecosystem around BIDS is constantly growing. Support for the standard has already been added to many conversion tools, quality assessment protocols, processing pipelines, databases and repositories.
